			<ns0:name>jvo...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/102292187274959663599/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">It looks like value ids for instruction operands start at N, where N is the number of module-level values.

This means that big linked bitcode files may end up using more bits just to get to N vs individual bitcode files where "N" for the particular bitcode module should be much smaller.

This may explain why bigger bitcode apps look so much worse compared to nexes.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2012-09-25T23:55:37.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2012-09-25T23:55:37.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:updates /><ns0:title>Comment 7 by jvo...@google.com</ns0:title><ns0:link href="http://code.google.com/p/nativeclient/issues/detail?id=3000#c7" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><ns0:link href="https://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/3000/comments/full/7" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /></ns0:entry>